hilosopher Lorraine Code's work. Since the publication of her 1987 book Epistemic Responsibility, Code has been at the forefront of linking epistemologies, ontologies, ethics, and epistemic injustice to guide critical frameworks for responsible, situated knowing and practices. This volume both enacts and expands Code's theories, epistemologies, and practices. It points to how concepts such as epistemic responsibility and approaches like ecological thinking are not only theoretical frameworks for knowing the world well; they are also practices and approaches that more and more feminists and critical thinkers are embodying in their work in order to think, write, and live critically and responsibly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aEnvironmental responsibility. 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAdkins, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Carolyn J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDatta, Ranjan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDionne, Émilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoucet, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoucet, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGardner, Catherine Villanueva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaloney, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula